    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-11-09T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-11-09T08:00:00-05:00" n="393"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d393">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">747C.00/11–954: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 393<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Greece (<persName corresp="#p_CCW1"
                            type="from">Cannon</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d393fn1">Repeated to London and USUN.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-11-09T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 9, 1954—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1014. Pass USUN. Last paragraph Department’s telegram 1073, November 5<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d393fn2">
                        <ref target="#d392">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</ref>
                    </note> in sharp contrast Foreign Office version of assurances Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> reported to have given Prime
                    Minister <persName corresp="#p_PA1">Papagos</persName> in Paris.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d393fn3">See <ref target="#d389">Document 389</ref>.</note>
                    According Foreign Office Prime Minister has definite impression Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> stated US would maintain
                    neutral position Cyprus issue, and specifically that US would not endeavor
                    influence other countries.</p>
                <p>Prime Minister also has further impression he received assurance from Secretary
                    that if any member US Government has been lobbying other <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> delegations against Greece on Cyprus issue it has been without
                    approval Secretary State, that Secretary promised look into this matter
                    immediately upon return Washington and to terminate such activities if they are
                    continuing and further that Secretary expressed intention communicate with Prime
                    Minister on this particular question.</p>
                <p>Embassy also informed that this is only point on which Prime Minister expects
                    hear from Secretary in response Marshal’s memorandum.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d393fn4">Reference presumably is to the memorandum by <persName
                            corresp="#p_PA1">Papagos</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>, Oct. 23; see <ref target="#d390fn3">footnote 3,
                            Document 390</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CCW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cannon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
